My apologies for the confusion. There should only be one template literal (`) in the "el.innerHTML" line. Here is the correct version of the function:

```javascript
function createNames() {
    const circle = document.getElementById('circle');
    for (let i = 0, len = names.length; i < len; i++) {
        let angle = 360 / len;
        let el = document.createElement('span');
        el.innerHTML = `<a href="#">${names[i][0]}<sub>${names[i][1]}</sub></a>`;
        el.style.transform = `translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(${angle * i}deg) translateY(-50%)`;
        el.style.top = '50%';
        el.style.left = '50%';
        circle.appendChild(el);
    }
}
```

The single template literal (`) is used to enclose the entire value for `el.innerHTML` and for `el.style.transform`. The `${}` syntax is used to insert JavaScript expressions, like `names[i][0]` and `names[i][1]`, within a string. In this case, there are three expressions to be included in their respective parts of the string:

1. `${names[i][0]}`: The name of the person/item
2. `${names[i][1]}`: The number to be displayed as a subscript
3. `${angle * i}`: The angle for the rotation transform

